<br>
&quot;Please&quot;<br>
This depends on the situation.  If you want to say something like &quot;please do X&quot;, that would be &quot;X shite kudasai&quot; (して下さい), where &quot;kudasai&quot; is functioning as &quot;please&quot;.  If you're begging or something &quot;onegai shimasu&quot; (お願いします) might be a better translation.  The usage of both words is kind of complicated so why don't you tell us more specifically what you're asking for.<br>
<br>
&quot;Thank you&quot;<br>
Well, from your post it looks sounds like you already know this one.  &quot;Arigatou gozaimasu&quot; (有り難うございます).<br>
<br>
&quot;No, no.  I think you'll find my defeat to be quite impossible&quot;<br>
...yeah, this is kind of tricky -- at least for me.  Its very James-Bond-supervillain-ish, and I'm not sure how one translates that sort of nuance.  The simplest way I can think of to get the idea across is: &quot;Ore ni katsu hazu ha nai&quot; (俺に勝つはずは無い), which is simply: &quot;You have no chance against me&quot;, or &quot;You can't possibly beat me&quot;.  Its more anime-like that James Bond, but anyway...<br>
<br>
&quot;Don't make me laugh&quot;<br>
Not sure on this.<br>
<br>
&quot;Surely you jest&quot;<br>
&quot;Maji ka?&quot; (マジか?)or just &quot;Maji?&quot; (マジ), would translate to &quot;Are you serious?&quot;  If you really want &quot;jest&quot; in there, you can use &quot;joudan ni chigainai&quot; (冗談に違いない), which is &quot;it must be a joke&quot; or &quot;you must be joking&quot;.<br>
<br>
&quot;Shutup&quot;<br>
Either &quot;Urusai&quot; (うるさい) or &quot;Damare&quot; (黙れ)work.<br>
<br>
&quot;Babe/kid&quot;<br>
Sorry I'm not sure on this one either.  Maybe &quot;boya&quot; (ボヤ) for &quot;kid&quot;, but they're hardly interchangable.<br>
<br>
&quot;It burns!&quot;<br>
I think &quot;Yaketeiru no yo!&quot; (焼けているのよ) works here.<br>
<br>
&quot;My head!&quot;<br>
Hmm, maybe &quot;Itama ga itai&quot; (頭が痛い) = &quot;my head hurts&quot;.  The Japanese use &quot;itai&quot; (痛い) or &quot;itee&quot; (いてェ−) instead of &quot;ouch&quot; so you might just drop the itama altogether, though I guess that's less specific.<br>
<br>
&quot;...strange&quot;<br>
Probably what you want is &quot;...okashii na&quot;, (おかしいな).  There are a lot of words for strange, though (&quot;hen&quot; (変), &quot;kimyou&quot; (奇妙), &quot;myou&quot; (妙), &quot;fushigi&quot; (不思議) off the top of my head).<br>
<br>
Hope that helps.  Back to cramming for exams.<br>
