<br>
Call it...extended context.<br>
<br>
This is a little hard to communicate, in English, because even though our history of kings, knights, dukes, farmers, and little boys is similar, English has very little grammar that reflects the social status of the speaker and listener.<br>
<br>
In English,<br>
If a 6-year-old-boy said &quot;It burns !&quot;, there'd be very little to distinguish it from the way a king would say &quot;it burns&quot; .<br>
Same with &quot;please&quot;, and so on.<br>
<br>
In Japanese, though, things vary RADICALLY.  Almost all the words change-- pronouns and verbs especially.<br>
<br>
For example, let's translate &quot;I&quot;.<br>
Male kid or relaxed Tokyo male:  Boku<br>
Mafia guy:  Washi or washya.<br>
Cute girl:   Atashi<br>
Hiroshima woman:  Uchi<br>
Normal office language:  Watashi<br>
Formal speaker:  Watakushi<br>
...and so on.<br>
<br>
Dizzying, isn't it ?<br>
<br>
For a small taste of this in English, consider that for a while, the ruling class in England spoke French, while the farmers spoke English/German.  That got reflected deeply in our language.  When an animal was alive, it took the German name, because it was being handled by the English/German groups of low status.<br>
<br>
Cow (from the German KUH)<br>
Swine (from the German SCHWIEN)<br>
<br>
After the animal was slaughtereed and cooked, however, it took on the nobility's names for things, from French:<br>
Beef  (from the French &quot;bif&quot;)<br>
Pork ....<br>
and so on.<br>
<br>
That's probably more than you wanted to know.<br>
Just...let us know the FULL context in which these Japanese phrases of yours are being used, and one of the posters here can give you an accurate translation.<br>
----<br>
BTW, I live in Hiroshima.  The Hiroshima accent is usually the accent used for Japanese mafia, so let me have the words you want translated, and I'll put them into deep, deep Hiroshima dialect.<br>
